events.description: The Australian stock market finished higher on Wednesday, driven by commodity-linked shares.
Escalating tensions between the US and Iran impacting bullion and oil prices.
China's activity in stockpiling metals contributing to a rebound in copper prices.

facts.fact_text: The S&P/ASX 200 finished 0.8% higher at 8,928 on Wednesday.

evidences.evidence_text: The S&P/ASX 200 finished 0.8% higher at 8,928 on Wednesday

facts.fact_text: The mining sub-index jumped 3.7%, its biggest intraday gain since April 10, 2025.

evidences.evidence_text: The heavyweight mining sub-index jumped 3.7%, its biggest intraday gain since April 10, 2025

facts.fact_text: BHP shares reached a record high of A$52.27.

evidences.evidence_text: BHP, Australia’s largest listed company, climbed as much as 4.5% to a record A$52.27

facts.fact_text: Tech stocks fell 9.4% to a two-year low.

evidences.evidence_text: Meanwhile, tech stocks plunged 9.4% to a two-year low

claims.claim_text: Higher interest rates support bank profitability in the long-term.

evidences.evidence_text: investors worried about AI creating more competition for software makers

claims.claim_text: Improved risk sentiment contributed to the metals rally.

evidences.evidence_text: copper rebounding on China stockpiling and improved risk sentiment
